</tr>
<tr data-end="2239" data-start="2176">
<td data-col-size="sm" data-end="2195" data-start="2176"><span style="font-size:16px;">Singapore</span></td>
<td data-col-size="sm" data-end="2239" data-start="2195"><span style="font-size:16px;">31%</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p data-end="2712" data-start="2323">&nbsp;</p>

<h3 data-end="2793" data-start="2714"><span style="font-size:20px;">ASEAN ministers are expected to discuss a suite of policy responses, including:</span></h3>

<ul data-end="3065" data-start="2795">
<li data-end="2864" data-start="2795">
<p data-end="2864" data-start="2797"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong data-end="2827" data-start="2797">Boosting intra-ASEAN trade</strong> to reduce reliance on global giants.</span></p>
</li>
<li data-end="2939" data-start="2865">
<p data-end="2939" data-start="2867"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong data-end="2902" data-start="2867">Diversifying trade partnerships</strong> with the EU, Japan, and South Korea.</span></p>
</li>
<li data-end="3002" data-start="2940">
<p data-end="3002" data-start="2942"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong data-end="2983" data-start="2942">Accelerating digital trade agreements</strong> within the region.</span></p>
</li>
<li data-end="3065" data-start="3003">
<p data-end="3065" data-start="3005"><span style="font-size:16px;"><strong data-end="3045" data-start="3005">Strengthening regional supply chains</strong> for key industries.</span></p>
</li>
</ul>

<h3 data-end="3102" data-start="3072">&nbsp;</h3>

<h2 data-end="3102" data-start="3072"><span style="font-size:22px;"><strong data-end="3102" data-start="3076">A Diplomatic Tightrope</strong></span></h2>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p data-end="3405" data-start="3104"><span style="font-size:16px;">Despite the criticism aimed at Washington&rsquo;s approach, ASEAN leaders are treading carefully. While the bloc wishes to uphold the multilateral trading system under the World Trade Organization (WTO), it also seeks to avoid provoking the U.S.&mdash;a critical investor and security partner in the Indo-Pacific. A senior diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity, told reporters: &ldquo;We&rsquo;re not looking to pick a fight, but we must protect our interests. The global economy can&rsquo;t function properly if trade rules are ignored or weaponized.&rdquo; ASEAN leaders will also explore fast-tracking the implementation of the <strong data-end="3766" data-start="3712">Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership (RCEP)</strong> &mdash; the world&rsquo;s largest trade deal &mdash; as a buffer against external shocks.</span></p>

<h3 data-end="3866" data-start="3845">&nbsp;</h3>

<h2 data-end="3866" data-start="3845"><span style="font-size:22px;"><strong data-end="3866" data-start="3849">Looking Ahead</strong></span></h2>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p data-end="4155" data-start="3868"><span style="font-size:16px;">With the summit underway, much attention is focused on whether ASEAN can deliver a unified message. The bloc&rsquo;s consensus-based approach often limits direct criticism, but the intensity of this year&rsquo;s statement signals a growing willingness to confront challenges to global trade head-on.</span></p>

<p data-end="4361" data-start="4157"><span style="font-size:16px;">As President Trump continues to reshape U.S. trade policy with more unilateral moves, analysts say Southeast Asia is being forced to choose between long-standing alliances and pragmatic economic survival.</span></p>',
