                'encode_title' => 'dhakas-urban-millennials-embrace-slow-living-as-an-antidote-to-daily-hustle',
                'seo_title' => NULL,
                'stitle' => NULL,
                'title' => 'Dhaka’s Urban Millennials Embrace ‘Slow Living’ as an Antidote to Daily Hustle',
                'news' => '<p data-end="530" data-start="227">In the heart of Bangladesh&rsquo;s fast-paced capital, a quiet revolution is taking place. Young professionals and millennials in Dhaka are increasingly embracing the global &lsquo;slow living&rsquo; movement&mdash;choosing mindfulness, minimalism, and quality time over consumerism and constant hustle.</p>

<p data-end="755" data-start="532">From cozy book caf&eacute;s in Dhanmondi to weekend pottery classes in Banani, urban dwellers are creating intentional pauses in their busy routines. This shift, many say, is about regaining control over their time and well-being.</p>

<p data-end="951" data-start="757"><strong data-end="815" data-start="757">&quot;I used to feel guilty for not being productive 24/7,&quot;</strong> says Rifa Mahmud, a 29-year-old graphic designer. <strong data-end="951" data-start="866">&quot;But now I&rsquo;ve realized that slowing down helps me think clearer and live better.&quot;</strong></p>

<p data-end="1253" data-start="953">The slow living trend, popularized in the West through movements like hygge in Denmark or lagom in Sweden, has taken on a unique Bangladeshi twist. Locals are reviving traditional leisure activities&mdash;such as rooftop gardening, handcrafts, and reading Bangla literature&mdash;as part of this lifestyle shift.</p>

<p data-end="1511" data-start="1255">Retailers and caf&eacute;s are also adapting. Businesses like <em data-end="1328" data-start="1310">The Lotus Lounge</em> in Gulshan offer &quot;no WiFi&quot; zones to encourage conversation and relaxation. Homegrown brands are launching minimalist, eco-conscious clothing lines and locally made wellness products.</p>

<p data-end="1795" data-start="1513"><strong data-end="1556" data-start="1513">Mental health experts applaud the trend</strong>, noting that Dhaka&rsquo;s intense work culture and traffic stress contribute to burnout. <strong data-end="1691" data-start="1641">&quot;Slow living offers a necessary mental detox,&quot;</strong> says Dr. Tanjina Rahman, a clinical psychologist. <strong data-end="1795" data-start="1742">&quot;It&rsquo;s not laziness&mdash;it&rsquo;s survival with intention.&quot;</strong></p>

<p data-end="1969" data-start="1797">Even social media is feeling the change. Influencers are switching gears from promoting luxury lifestyles to sharing moments of stillness, journaling, or slow food recipes.</p>

<p data-end="2227" data-start="1971"><strong data-end="1987" data-start="1971">What&rsquo;s Next?</strong><br data-end="1990" data-start="1987" />
With growing awareness, the slow living movement is expected to grow, especially among the educated middle class. While challenges remain&mdash;such as the culture of overtime and digital overload&mdash;many believe this new mindset is here to stay.</p>

<p data-end="2318" data-start="2229"><strong data-end="2271" data-start="2229">&quot;Slowing down doesn&rsquo;t mean giving up,&quot;</strong> says Rifa. <strong data-end="2318" data-start="2283">&quot;It means living with meaning.&quot;</strong></p>',
