            58 => 
            array (
                'id' => 106,
                'uuid' => 'e661fefe-689e-4bd4-ac37-73a037fab500',
                'news_id' => 106,
                'language_id' => 1,
                'category_id' => 55,
                'sub_category_id' => 61,
                'encode_title' => 'traditional-superfoods-make-a-comeback-in-modern-diets',
                'seo_title' => NULL,
                'stitle' => NULL,
                'title' => 'Traditional Superfoods Make a Comeback in Modern Diets',
                'news' => '<p data-end="472" data-start="230">As global health trends evolve, a surprising shift is happening right here at home: Bangladeshi superfoods, once dismissed as &quot;old-fashioned,&quot; are regaining popularity among health-conscious youth and wellness experts.</p>

<p data-end="691" data-start="474">Items like <strong data-end="511" data-start="485">kalijira (black cumin)</strong>, <strong data-end="534" data-start="513">methi (fenugreek)</strong>, <strong data-end="564" data-start="536">amla (Indian gooseberry)</strong>, and <strong data-end="593" data-start="570">shutki (dried fish)</strong> are making their way from grandmothers&rsquo; kitchens to trendy health caf&eacute;s and urban grocery stores.</p>

<p data-end="943" data-start="693"><strong data-end="770" data-start="693">&quot;We used to overlook these ingredients in favor of imported supplements,&quot;</strong> says Nayeem Hassan, a 34-year-old nutritionist and co-founder of <em data-end="852" data-start="836">Wellness Dhaka</em>, a local health consultancy. <strong data-end="943" data-start="882">&quot;Now we&rsquo;re realizing the power of our own food heritage.&quot;</strong></p>

<p data-end="1161" data-start="945">At <em data-end="965" data-start="948">Roots &amp; Rituals</em>, a new caf&eacute; in Dhanmondi, items like kalijira-infused parathas and amla smoothies are becoming top sellers. The caf&eacute; promotes clean eating by blending traditional wisdom with modern presentation.</p>

<p data-end="1391" data-start="1163"><strong data-end="1181" data-start="1163">Why the Shift?</strong><br data-end="1184" data-start="1181" />
Many urbanites are growing tired of processed food and artificial diets. Influencers, fitness coaches, and even some physicians are promoting a return to &quot;ancestral nutrition&quot;&mdash;natural, local, and affordable.</p>

<p data-end="1621" data-start="1393"><strong data-end="1440" data-start="1393">&quot;Kalijira is a powerful anti-inflammatory,&quot;</strong> explains Dr. Saima Noor, an integrative health specialist. <strong data-end="1621" data-start="1500">&quot;Combined with turmeric, it becomes a potent immunity booster&mdash;something we all became more aware of during COVID-19.&quot;</strong></p>

<p data-end="1778" data-start="1623">The movement is also about identity. Young Bangladeshis are seeking ways to connect with their roots, not just through fashion and music, but through food.</p>

<p data-end="1997" data-start="1780"><strong data-end="1816" data-start="1780">TikTok and Instagram are buzzing</strong> with #DeshiWellness trends&mdash;showing easy recipes like methi tea for digestion, roasted shutki with olive oil for protein, and shorbot made with local fruits instead of sugary sodas.</p>

<p data-end="2204" data-start="1999"><strong data-end="2022" data-start="1999">Is It Just a Trend?</strong><br data-end="2025" data-start="2022" />
Experts believe this is more than a passing phase. As Bangladesh&rsquo;s middle class grows more health-conscious, the demand for affordable, accessible superfoods will likely continue.</p>

<p data-end="2344" data-start="2206"><strong data-end="2275" data-start="2206">&quot;The solutions to better health may not lie in a foreign bottle,&quot;</strong> says Nayeem. <strong data-end="2344" data-start="2289">&quot;They might be right inside your own kitchen rack.&quot;</strong></p>

<p data-end="2482" data-start="2346">Whether it&rsquo;s for health, heritage, or simple taste, traditional Bangladeshi ingredients are making a modern comeback&mdash;one dish at a time.</p>',
