            259 => 
            array (
                'id' => 315,
                'uuid' => 'd6bb93f0-3486-4292-bd4f-b131c181ba3b',
                'news_id' => 315,
                'language_id' => 1,
                'category_id' => 88,
                'sub_category_id' => NULL,
                'encode_title' => 'social-media-becomes-the-new-job-market-as-digital-careers-rise-in-2025',
                'seo_title' => NULL,
                'stitle' => NULL,
                'title' => 'Social Media Becomes the New Job Market as Digital Careers Rise in 2025',
                'news' => '<p data-end="641" data-start="306"><strong data-end="315" data-start="306">Dhaka</strong> &ndash; In 2025, social media has evolved far beyond entertainment and status updates &mdash; it&#39;s now a booming hub for business, employment, and personal branding. From job seekers to entrepreneurs, millions are using platforms like LinkedIn, Facebook, TikTok, and Instagram to generate income and build careers in the digital economy.</p>

<p data-end="951" data-start="643">With the growth of freelancing and e-commerce, social media has become the <strong data-end="732" data-start="718">new r&eacute;sum&eacute;</strong> for many in Bangladesh and around the world. Online platforms now serve as digital offices, marketplaces, and career development spaces, offering both opportunities and challenges in the rapidly changing job landscape.</p>

<p data-end="1286" data-start="953"><strong data-end="965" data-start="953">LinkedIn</strong>, once limited to corporate professionals, is now attracting students, freelancers, and small business owners. Job postings, networking groups, and skill-building videos are seeing record engagement. In Bangladesh alone, LinkedIn users have crossed <strong data-end="1227" data-start="1214">7 million</strong>, with many companies hiring directly through the platform.</p>

<p data-end="1469" data-start="1288">&ldquo;I got my last two projects through LinkedIn,&rdquo; said Arafat Rahman, a freelance graphic designer from Khulna. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t need an agency &mdash; just a strong profile and a portfolio online.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="1750" data-start="1471">Meanwhile, <strong data-end="1508" data-start="1482">Facebook and Instagram</strong> are fueling the rise of small online businesses. According to a report by the e-Commerce Association of Bangladesh (e-CAB), over <strong data-end="1666" data-start="1638">500,000 small businesses</strong> now operate via social media, many run by women, students, and rural entrepreneurs.</p>

<p data-end="1997" data-start="1752">&ldquo;The demand for digital marketing skills has exploded,&rdquo; said Tanima Haque, who runs a digital training center in Rajshahi. &ldquo;Young people are learning SEO, video editing, and social media management because these are real, bankable skills today.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="2330" data-start="1999">The phenomenon of <strong data-end="2037" data-start="2017">content creators</strong> or influencers has also grown into a full-fledged profession. From YouTubers and TikTokers to Instagram vloggers, creators are partnering with brands and earning through sponsored content, affiliate marketing, and live streams. Some are even launching their own product lines and mobile apps.</p>

<p data-end="2574" data-start="2332">But the trend has its drawbacks. Experts warn of rising competition, burnout, and income instability in the influencer economy. Platforms frequently change their algorithms, making it hard for creators to maintain steady reach and engagement.</p>

<p data-end="2774" data-start="2576">&ldquo;There is a dark side to social media fame,&rdquo; said Dr. Tasfia Nawar, a media analyst. &ldquo;Many creators feel pressure to constantly produce content and stay relevant, which affects their mental health.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="2917" data-start="2776">In response, several startups are building tools to help digital workers better manage income, track analytics, and protect their well-being.</p>

<p data-end="3220" data-start="2919">Government initiatives are also catching up. The ICT Division of Bangladesh has launched new training programs to promote <strong data-end="3087" data-start="3041">youth employment through digital platforms</strong>, especially in rural areas. Some universities have even added social media and digital entrepreneurship courses to their curriculum.</p>

<p data-end="3399" data-start="3222">As the lines blur between personal and professional life, experts stress the need for <strong data-end="3364" data-start="3308">digital ethics, transparency, and financial literacy</strong> in this new era of online careers.</p>

<p data-end="3571" data-start="3401">&ldquo;Social media is no longer optional,&rdquo; said Imran Kabir, a career coach in Dhaka. &ldquo;If you&rsquo;re not on it, you&rsquo;re invisible &mdash; but you also need to know how to use it wisely.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="3747" data-start="3573">With digital connectivity growing every day, social media isn&rsquo;t just shaping how people communicate &mdash; it&rsquo;s reshaping <strong data-end="3726" data-start="3690">how people work, earn, and dream</strong> in the 21st century.</p>',
