            260 => 
            array (
                'id' => 316,
                'uuid' => 'e3b4facf-743b-456d-929a-f258009cd39f',
                'news_id' => 316,
                'language_id' => 1,
                'category_id' => 88,
                'sub_category_id' => NULL,
                'encode_title' => 'from-trends-to-identity-how-social-media-is-shaping-youth-culture-in-2025',
                'seo_title' => NULL,
                'stitle' => NULL,
                'title' => 'From Trends to Identity: How Social Media is Shaping Youth Culture in 2025',
                'news' => '<p data-end="652" data-start="270"><strong data-end="279" data-start="270">Dhaka</strong> &ndash; Social media has become the heartbeat of youth culture in 2025, influencing everything from fashion and music to language and identity. For millions of teenagers and young adults in Bangladesh and across the globe, platforms like TikTok, Instagram, and YouTube are not just digital tools &mdash; they are cultural spaces where trends are born, shared, and reshaped every hour.</p>

<p data-end="993" data-start="654">According to a recent study by the Centre for Digital Youth, over <strong data-end="760" data-start="720">85% of teenagers in urban Bangladesh</strong> spend more than three hours daily on social media. The report highlights how these platforms have evolved into powerful agents of influence &mdash; changing how the younger generation dresses, speaks, socializes, and even views the world.</p>

<p data-end="1225" data-start="995">&ldquo;I get all my ideas from social media &mdash; what to wear, what to listen to, what new spots to hang out at,&rdquo; said Samiya Rahman, a 17-year-old student from Dhaka. &ldquo;Sometimes I feel like I&rsquo;m living two lives &mdash; one offline, one online.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="1545" data-start="1227"><strong data-end="1237" data-start="1227">TikTok</strong>, in particular, remains the most influential platform among youth. Viral challenges, dance routines, cooking hacks, fashion transitions, and motivational reels dominate the feed. Bangladeshi content creators like Tanzim Khan, Oishee Rahman, and Fahim Vlogs have become household names among Gen Z followers.</p>

<p data-end="1805" data-start="1547"><strong data-end="1560" data-start="1547">Instagram</strong>, on the other hand, is still the go-to for curated personal branding. Young people use Stories and Reels to document their daily lives, achievements, activism, and style &mdash; often edited with filters, music, and effects to match aesthetic trends.</p>

<p data-end="2019" data-start="1807">But with this hyper-connectivity comes a complex web of pressures. Digital comparison, fear of missing out (FOMO), and the pursuit of perfection have led to rising anxiety, low self-esteem, and screen dependency.</p>

<p data-end="2282" data-start="2021">&ldquo;Social media is giving young people a platform to express themselves, but also putting them under enormous pressure to look perfect and stay &lsquo;on trend,&rsquo;&rdquo; said Dr. Mahbuba Sultana, a child psychologist. &ldquo;We need more open conversations around digital wellness.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="2633" data-start="2284">Peer influence is also shifting. Instead of traditional role models like athletes or actors, teens are now following <strong data-end="2422" data-start="2401">micro-influencers</strong> and content creators who speak their language and share their struggles. Topics like mental health, gender identity, climate change, and self-love are gaining traction &mdash; often started by young users themselves.</p>

<p data-end="2857" data-start="2635">In response to growing concerns, some schools are introducing <strong data-end="2720" data-start="2697">digital citizenship</strong> classes to teach students how to use social media responsibly, spot misinformation, and balance screen time with real-life interactions.</p>

<p data-end="2994" data-start="2859">Despite the concerns, many believe social media has given the youth more <strong data-end="2966" data-start="2932">freedom, visibility, and voice</strong> than any generation before.</p>

<p data-end="3209" data-start="2996">&ldquo;I&rsquo;ve learned more about confidence, culture, and creativity from my TikTok feed than from my textbooks,&rdquo; said Ayman Nafi, an 18-year-old aspiring content creator from Sylhet. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s where we all connect and grow.&rdquo;</p>

<p data-end="3450" data-start="3211">As the youth continue to define their generation online, experts call for greater <strong data-end="3337" data-start="3293">digital literacy, parental understanding</strong>, and <strong data-end="3370" data-start="3343">platform responsibility</strong> to ensure that the online world remains a space for empowerment &mdash; not pressure.</p>',
