<p data-end="2951" data-start="2823"><span style="font-family:Verdana,Geneva,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size:12px;"><strong data-end="2837" data-start="2823">Key Shift:</strong> The rise of the &ldquo;nones&rdquo; (religiously unaffiliated) is among the most dramatic religious shifts in recent history.</span></span></p>

<p data-end="2951" data-start="2823">&nbsp;</p>

<p data-end="672" data-start="303"><span style="font-family:Verdana,Geneva,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size:12px;">Immigration has always been a cornerstone of the American story. But over the past 60 years, the origins of the U.S. foreign-born population have changed dramatically &mdash; shifting from a Europe-dominated pattern to one led by Latin America, Asia, and more recently, Africa. These demographic transformations reflect both global trends and U.S. immigration policy reforms.</span></span></p>

<p data-end="672" data-start="303">&nbsp;</p>

